rs. Constitutional Conscience concludes that the need for these qualities in judges—as well as lawyers and citizens—is implicit in our constitutional practices, and that without them judicial review would forfeit both its own integrity and the credibility of the courts themselves.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aConstitutional lawxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aConstitutional lawzUnited States. 0aJudgesxUnited States. 0aJudgeszUnited States. 0aJudicial discretionxUnited States. 0aJudicial discretionzUnited States. 0aJudicial processxUnited States. 0aJudicial processzUnited States. 0aJustice, Administration ofxUnited States. 0aJustice, Administration ofzUnited States. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226677309423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226677309.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles